<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFCB6A74F7F0954F17EEBF16" pageId="48" pageNumber="806" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFCB6A74F7F0954F17EEBF16" blockId="48.[2059,2652,633,1060]" pageId="48" pageNumber="806">
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCB6A74F7F0954F171DB805" authorityName="Laurie &amp; Hill" authorityYear="1954" box="[2060,2333,790,823]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="806" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microdon">Nyctophilus microdon</taxonomicName>
is the only representative of the highly distinctive 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCB6A74F6559567141BB86D" authorityName="Laurie &amp; Hill" authorityYear="1954" box="[2473,2587,830,863]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="806" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microdon">microdon</taxonomicName>
species group. There is apparently an unnamed species of 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCB6A74F6D095D517C0B89F" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1821" box="[2348,2496,908,941]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="806" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Nyctophilus</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFFCB6A74F5F995D516BFB8E4" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="48" pageNumber="806">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
that has similar glans penis morphology to N. 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCB6A74F6D895821796B8CE" authorityName="Laurie &amp; Hill" authorityYear="1954" box="[2340,2454,987,1020]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Nyctophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="806" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microdon">microdon</taxonomicName>
according to H. E. Parnaby in 2009. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
